{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Hugh of St. Victor (b. ca. 1097-1101; d. 1141) was a canon regular who entered the Abbey of St. Victor in Paris.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Probably a student of William of Champeaux, he became a leading master in the abbey's school.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "The two most important are De sacramentis christianae fidei, the first theological summa, and Didascalicon, which proposed an influential framework for scientific inquiry and biblical interpretation.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Hugh was a master in a school and counts as a scholastic author, even though he comes before the rise of university scholasticism and before the Latin West's rediscovery of the integral Aristotle.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "Like most medieval authors, Hugh is more a theologian than a philosopher.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "At some risk of oversimplification, we can identify three principles at work in Hugh's thought.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "The first is the chronological distinction between institution and restoration.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Institution is God's work of creating everything in its original state; restoration refers to God's subsequent work of bringing everything back from evil to even greater good.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "The second principle is semiotic.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "For Hugh, all creatures are signs of God, and man is an especially good sign of God; further, certain creatures are used by God as signs, above all in Scripture.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "The third principle is causal.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "For Hugh, all things are bound up in causal networks.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Of these three principles, the causal is the most basic.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Hugh's division of the sciences reflects his respect for the whole range of human intellectual endeavor.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "'The arts' or 'philosophy' has four divisions: theoretical, practical, mechanical (including this is a Hugonian innovation), and logical.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Hugh reduces the basic divine attributes to power, will (goodness), and wisdom.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "Hugh follows Augustine in holding that time began with creation.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "He also holds that the world began in a relatively unformed state and was later given (more) form by God.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "Hugh holds that God governs all of creation.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "This raises difficulties that call on much of his skill.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "Hugh has a strong doctrine of man as the image of God.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "He sees man as including both soul and body, but he has a strong tendency to identify man with the soul alone.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "The work of restoration is spread out over a long expanse of time, starting right after the fall, even before the first revelation to the Jews.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU24": {
      "text": "Hugh's Christology is basically orthodox; he shows good mastery of the basic patristic teachings on person and nature.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU25": {
      "text": "It was he who made the decisive contribution to Christian theology of characterizing a sacrament in the full sense as not just a sign but a sign instituted by Christ for the purpose of conveying what it signifies.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU26": {
      "text": "Hugh had a great influence over the members of his own school, Richard of St. Victor above all.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU27": {
      "text": "In an even more long-lasting way, he influenced Peter Lombard, whose impact on later scholastic thought is hard to overstate.",
      "label": "premise"
    }
  },
