{
  "ADUs": {
    "1": {
      "text": "Hugh of St. Victor (b. ca. 1097-1101; d. 1141) was a canon regular who entered the Abbey of St. Victor in Paris.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "2": {
      "text": "His writings encompass a wide range of commentaries, treatises, and mystical works. The two most important are De sacramentis christianae fidei, the first theological summa, and Didascalicon, which proposed an influential framework for scientific inquiry and biblical interpretation.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "3": {
      "text": "Hugh was a master in a school and counts as a scholastic author, even though he comes before the rise of university scholasticism and before the Latin West's rediscovery of the integral Aristotle.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "4": {
      "text": "Like most medieval authors, Hugh is more a theologian than a philosopher. His main categories and concerns are determined by the Christian faith, he appeals to revelation freely, and he seldom engages in independent philosophical inquiries.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "5": {
      "text": "At the same time, however, he does distinguish philosophy from theology, and he sees a real (if secondary) role for reason acting without special guidance from faith in an attempt to grasp the works of institution",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "6": {
      "text": "For Hugh, God is neither wholly known by us nor wholly unknown",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "7": {
      "text": "We know about God in two basic ways, reason and revelation; each of these is subdivided into external and internal indications of God's existence",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "8": {
      "text": "If Hugh sometimes lacks the great sophistication of later scholastic thinkers, at the same time the relative lack of complexity of his thought makes it easier for him to achieve and expound an overall vision without getting distracted by technical issues.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "9": {
      "text": "He balances concern for the natural with a concern to place it in the greater supernatural context.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
